{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17477148","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17477148"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:58:02+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:58:02+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14183"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14183","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14183"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.16,0.28,0.51,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6866"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"89445"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6866","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6866"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14183"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"73578"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"36"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1217"},{"type":"tags","id":"1239"},{"type":"tags","id":"1254"},{"type":"tags","id":"2891"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4970"},{"type":"tags","id":"4983"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"6400"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11643"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"15639"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30477"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30479"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44202"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"89445","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/89445"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 15-year-old boy presents to the Emergency Department with a two-day history of right testicular pain and swelling. He also reports feeling feverish and having a sore throat for the past week. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. His immunisation status is unclear. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell. His pulse rate is 100/min, blood pressure 110/70 mmHg, respiratory rate 18/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 38.5\u00b0C. The right side of his scrotum is swollen and tender. His right testicle is enlarged and painful to palpation. There is no erythema of the scrotal skin. Abdominal examination is unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Intravenous corticosteroids","Immediate surgical exploration","Oral antibiotics","Ultrasound of the scrotum","Fine needle aspiration of the testicle"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis case presents a 15-year-old boy with symptoms suggestive of orchitis, possibly due to mumps virus given the preceding sore throat and fever. The most appropriate next step in management is to perform an \u003Cstrong\u003Eultrasound of the scrotum\u003C/strong\u003E. Ultrasound is the imaging modality of choice for evaluating testicular pain and swelling when torsion is not suspected. Whilst most cases of torsion can be diagnosed on a clinical assessment, even when such a diagnosis is thought less likely than orchitis or a tumour, it is prudent to perform an ultrasound examination. Apart from excluding torsion, it can help differentiate between various causes of acute scrotal pain, including orchitis, epididymitis, and testicular tumours. In this case, ultrasound would likely show an enlarged, hypoechoic testicle with increased blood flow, consistent with orchitis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EImmediate surgical exploration\u003C/strong\u003E is not indicated as the first step in this scenario. While it is crucial in cases of suspected testicular torsion, the history and examination findings here are more consistent with orchitis. The gradual onset over two days and the presence of systemic symptoms make torsion less likely. If torsion was suspected based on sudden onset of pain or other clinical features, immediate surgical exploration would be warranted without delay for imaging.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral antibiotics\u003C/strong\u003E would be appropriate if bacterial epididymo-orchitis was suspected. However, given the patient\u0027s age and the preceding viral symptoms, viral orchitis (likely mumps) is more probable. Antibiotics are not effective against viral infections.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFine needle aspiration of the testicle\u003C/strong\u003E is not routinely performed in cases of suspected orchitis. It carries risks of infection and damage to the testicle and is generally reserved for specific situations such as suspected testicular abscesses or tumours.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous corticosteroids\u003C/strong\u003E are not typically used in the initial management of viral orchitis. While they may have a role in reducing inflammation in severe cases, they are not a first-line treatment and should be used cautiously, if at all, in the context of a possible viral infection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAfter confirming the diagnosis with ultrasound, management of viral orchitis is primarily supportive, including rest, analgesia (such as NSAIDs), scrotal support, and ice packs. If mumps is confirmed, the patient should be isolated to prevent spread of the infection. It\u0027s also important to check the patient\u0027s vaccination status and consider updating it if necessary to prevent future infections.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Mumps is a common cause of orchitis in adolescent males, especially in unvaccinated individuals.","Ultrasound is the imaging modality of choice for evaluating testicular pain and swelling when torsion is not suspected.","Management of viral orchitis is primarily supportive, including rest, analgesia, and scrotal support."],"references":["Wu H, Wang F, Tang D, Han D. Mumps Orchitis: Clinical Aspects and Mechanisms. Front Immunol. 2021 Mar 18;12:582946. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/33815357/","Hoffmann K, Gopal M. Paediatric acute epididymo-orchitis temporally related to SARS-CoV-2 infection: A case series and review of the literature. J Pediatr Urol. 2024 Feb;20(1):91-94. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/37806834/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"73578"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14183"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"73578","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/73578"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-09T16:46:40+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-09T16:47:36+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6866"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"89445"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":nul